About: I think this is about the well-known "PrisonersDilemma". This dilemma explores human individuality and the ability for cooperation between two parties. What I remember is that this dilemma suggests two individuals won't cooperate even though doing so would benefit them both. This is because people always seek their own benefit before the common good, especially if there's no trust within the ÔdilemmaÕ. This distrustÑbelieving the other person won't act for mutual benefit but rather their own gain, consequently harming the otherÑcauses both parties to make a less beneficial choice.
Advice1: I think the best way to play is to always seek the benefit of both parties since that way both sides win and no one is harmed. This is the theory, but I don't think it's wrong to seek one's own benefit in these types of situations. I believe reality is harsher than we think, and perfect scenarios don't always existÑjust like there aren't perfect people. Therefore, I believe the best way to play this game is by cooperating, but one shouldn't feel bad about the decision made. Every action we take has its benefits and consequences.
